{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:07:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:07:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14023"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14023"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.26,0.32,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6672"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1594"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11000"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the nephrology outpatient clinic with three months of low energy and occasionally falling asleep at work. She has not noticed bleeding, change in bowel habit or other symptoms. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, dyslipidaemia and proteinuric chronic kidney disease stage 4 with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 22 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Her medications include telmisartan, hydrochlorothiazide, amlodipine, linagliptin, sevelamer, calcitriol and atorvastatin. She reports a varied diet including meat and fish and does not take any regular supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is pallor of the conjunctiva and palmar creases. Recent investigations reveal: haemoglobin 89 g/L (115-165), serum ferritin 80 \u03bcg/L (30-300), transferrin saturation 18% (20-50).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Organise intravenous iron infusion","Commence erythropoiesis-stimulating agent","Check erythropoietin level","Organise blood transfusion to aim haemoglobin above 100 g/L","Organise a colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnaemia in chronic kidney disease is multifactorial, commonly driven by reduced endogenous erythropoietin and iron-restricted erythropoiesis. Functional iron deficiency is frequent due to inflammation and impaired iron utilisation, leading to low transferrin saturation despite ferritin that may be low or within the reference interval. Repletion of iron stores, often intravenously in advanced chronic kidney disease, improves haemoglobin and responsiveness to erythropoiesis-stimulating agents while reducing required doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrganise intravenous iron infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the best next step. The haemoglobin of 89 g/L with transferrin saturation 18% and ferritin 80 \u03bcg/L indicates iron-restricted erythropoiesis in chronic kidney disease. Intravenous iron is preferred in stage 4 chronic kidney disease because oral absorption is often inadequate; optimising iron stores before erythropoiesis-stimulating agents improves efficacy and may obviate or delay their need.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence erythropoiesis-stimulating agent\u003C/strong\u003E is premature before iron repletion. Without adequate iron availability, the rise in haemoglobin is suboptimal and higher doses may be needed, increasing risks such as hypertension and thromboembolic events. Guidelines recommend correcting iron deficiency first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECheck erythropoietin level\u003C/strong\u003E is not useful for decision-making. In chronic kidney disease, erythropoietin levels are often inappropriately low relative to anaemia, but measuring them does not change initial management; addressing iron deficiency precedes consideration of erythropoiesis-stimulating agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrganise blood transfusion to aim haemoglobin above 100 g/L\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in a stable outpatient with chronic kidney disease\u2013related anaemia. Transfusions carry risks and sensitisation relevant to future transplantation and are reserved for severe symptoms, haemodynamic instability or failure of other therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrganise a colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not the immediate step given no gastrointestinal symptoms and iron indices consistent with functional iron deficiency in chronic kidney disease. Gastrointestinal evaluation becomes appropriate if there are alarm features, positive faecal occult blood testing or failure to respond to iron repletion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Optimise iron stores before starting erythropoiesis-stimulating agents in chronic kidney disease to improve response and reduce dose requirements.","Functional iron deficiency in chronic kidney disease is suggested by low transferrin saturation with low or mid-range ferritin and warrants iron replacement, often intravenously.","Erythropoiesis-stimulating agents are considered after iron repletion and exclusion of other correctable causes of anaemia."],"references":["Official journal of the international society of nephrology Clinical Practice Guideline for Anemia in Chronic Kidney Disease. In: KDIGO [Online]. 2012. Available at: https://kdigo.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/KDIGO-2012-Anemia-Guideline-English.pdf","Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health\rAustralia, Melbourne, 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94199"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14023"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94199"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-25T18:22:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-25T18:24:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6672"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG